            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>And then&hellip; there&rsquo;s the offensive line. The most criticized (sometimes justifiably so, sometimes not) unit on the team brings in the 40th-ranked offensive lineman in the country, Laken Tomlinson, next season. The most important thing about Tomlinson, though, is his size&mdash;he&rsquo;s 6-foot-5, 285 pounds, which means with just an offseason or two of being in Duke&rsquo;s strength and conditioning program, he can easily break 300 pounds. I would hope that this is the type of offensive lineman Cutcliffe continues to recruit, because it&rsquo;s really the only type that can play in a balanced offense.</p>
<p>But perhaps more significant than anything Duke has is on its roster is what the ACC doesn&rsquo;t&mdash;a powerhouse. Gone are the days when it was Florida State at the top and everyone else fighting for second place, and Virginia Tech gave up its perch as the conference&rsquo;s best this season. Today&rsquo;s king of the hill is Georgia Tech. Next year, it could be Miami&hellip; or North Carolina&hellip; or even N.C. State.</p>
<p>The point is, you won&rsquo;t have a program that reloads instead of rebuilding every year at the pinnacle. Duke&rsquo;s got the bare fundamentals you need to be a winning program&mdash;a smart, flexible head coach and a steady, mistake-free quarterback. But in order to become a championship program, it&rsquo;s going to have to find a way to upgrade those three elements: defense, athletic difference-makers on offense and a better offensive line.</p>
<p>Hey, it might be a little crazy. But I&rsquo;m just keeping it real, like I always have. It just so happens this time, the reality is Duke might be a championship squad in a few years.</p>

